%N A395333 Largest n-digit base-3 deletable prime.
%C A395333 A base-3 deletable prime is a prime whose base-3 representation can be reduced to the single-digit prime 2 by deleting one digit at a time, without ever creating a leading zero, so that every intermediate value is prime. a(n) is the largest such prime with exactly n digits in base 3. This is the base-3 analog of A125590 (base 10).
%H A395333 Daniel Okwor, <a href="/A395333/b395333.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..35</a>
%e A395333 a(2) = 7: in base 3, 7 is written 21; deleting the digit 1 leaves 2, which is prime.
%e A395333 a(4) = 73: in base 3, 73 is written 2201; the deletions 2201 -> 201 -> 21 -> 2 (base 3) correspond to the primes 73, 19, 7, 2.
%o A395333 (Python)
%o A395333 from sympy import isprime
%o A395333 def to3(n):
%o A395333     s=""
%o A395333     while n: s=str(n%3)+s; n//=3
%o A395333     return s
%o A395333 def deletable(p):
%o A395333     s=to3(p)
%o A395333     if len(s)==1: return isprime(p)
%o A395333     for i in range(len(s)):
%o A395333         t=s[:i]+s[i+1:]
%o A395333         if t[0]=="0": continue
%o A395333         v=int(t,3)
%o A395333         if isprime(v) and deletable(v): return True
%o A395333     return False
%o A395333 def a(n):
%o A395333     for p in range(3**n-1, 3**(n-1)-1, -1):
%o A395333         if isprime(p) and deletable(p): return p
%o A395333 print([a(n) for n in range(1,12)])
%Y A395333 Cf. A096236, A125589, A125590, A305352, A395332.
